answers.text: @y4d0_b132 so it's hard to differentiate between the country and language and citizen and ethnicity (india-thamizh-indian-thamizhar) without a human reader who is familiar with context or is able to catch on and clarify ambiguities. That's why human translators are very important for grammar-heavy languages unlike 华语

@y4d0_b132 moreover if there's instruction to be given, I don't want Google translator to be rude and say "1m thalli nil" but respectful "1m thalli nilLUNGAL - 1m away stand-you-honourable", or even "1m thalli nirkavum - 1m away stand-need". So, only Google translator can do so much. The worst thing is that every single Singaporean Chinese says "do you speak Indian" because there are 26 different languages and they aren't even close dialects like hokkien is to teochew or canto or mandarin - they are super different languages. Even indon-malay differences are put to shame. It's like asking if you speak "European". So, I noticed the screen cap said "I don't speak bangla" it's bengali. The problem comes in word choices - if I type "I don't speak India", the resulting in tamil will be "naan indiyaa peesavillai" which is actually "I did not speak india". What should be said is "ennakku tamizh peesya varaathu" or "me-to tamil to-speak comes-not-(action by inhumane doer). You may say, will ok fix Google make it replace india or bangla accordingly. But then, what if I'm asking if you're a Bangladeshi? Are you Bangladesh national? (I bet some didn't know all the mengaali kia don't come from India) are you Indian

@moist._.mizu I've used Google translate when learning mandarin Chinese (Btw I highly recommend pleco app), malay and tamil. Chinese sentences just sound off because of how English phrases are made, but sentences are fine. Malay also a bit weird (I find eng-indon much better, then just swap the indon words for more relavant malay terms like bisa-boleh). Tamil tho is a hot mess. Bangladeshi languages, like tamil, has a cancerous but very rich and complex grammar. Slightly worse than Korean/Japanese (if you know em). The biggest issue is the word order is different (verb goes to end instead of in middle). the second issue is that like English has -Ed and -ing, tamil (ik the focus is on Bangladeshi, but it relates) there is a lot, and it includes the tense, continuation, passive/active marker, whether it's not transitive, who is doing it - is it girl, guy, thing, someone respectable? Japanese and Korean speakers call this honorifics, and singular/plural - is it us, you all, them all, those things all). A simple sentence like (I like this) in malay is "aku suka ni", in chinese is "wo xihuan zhege 我喜欢这个＂ but tamil is "ennakku ithu pidichirukku" en=me (obj form), -akku=towards(me), ithu=this, pidi=like -chi=currently (used to bridge secondary verb to the primary modal verb following) -iru=have -kku=currently. But that's spoken tamil, like "this ain't rite vs this is not rite". In written tamil (which you ask Google translate) is "ennakku ithu pidithirukkirathu" which is different in the verb suffix: -chi- is now -tthi- since the consonant changes when spoken like "apa vs ape" , -kku is now -kirathu which is -kir- present non continuous tense, and -athu which implies an non-human object (ithu/this) is performing the action. This should make your head scratch because is it not "me" who is liking the object, so I'm "doing" it? Ye that's the problem, you dont "like" something. You may "love" something but it's pretty odd, no kink shaming tho, so only having objects being liked by you, which means the word is (not passive but) intrabsitive like "I ran" vs "I ran the machine" which is  differrnt in tamil: "naan oodinen" vs "நான் machine-ai otdinen".
